bug.short_desc: EFI: Problem loading in-kernel X.509 certificate (-22)

Response to Comment 17: An excellent question. As operating systems are increasingly complex, I am not sure how to answer without knowing: 1. How do we decide whether one of several current functional problems are due to this issue? Wireless networking cards not being activated? Mysterious graphics bugs? How about high battery use or issues with Nvidia Optimus? 2. How can we predict or check when manufacturer signed code will need to run but cannot?

(In reply to Phil V from comment #18) > Response to Comment 17: > > An excellent question. As operating systems are increasingly complex, I am > not sure how to answer without knowing: > > 1. How do we decide whether one of several current functional problems are > due to this issue? Wireless networking cards not being activated? Mysterious > graphics bugs? How about high battery use or issues with Nvidia Optimus? > > 2. How can we predict or check when manufacturer signed code will need to > run but cannot? Can you attach the full output of dmesg on the newest kernel you have installed? It's rather unlikely that either case you describe above is related to this issue. The issues in your case #1 are likely caused by in-kernel or driver issues. No 3rd party signs the kernel or drivers we provided, so rejected or invalid keys wouldn't matter. The issue in case #2 in relation to how the kernel uses the UEFI certificates would only matter if you're using a driver signed by a 3rd party that has a key installed in your UEFI database. That is fairly rare. Microcode and firmware is not signed nor is a signature checked for it.
